    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that can navigate and interact with web applications on behalf of users?", "option_a": "Parse HTML and click randomly until the goal is achieved", "option_b": "Only interact with APIs, never web UIs", "option_c": "Use a structured approach: identify page elements and their purposes from DOM/accessibility tree, plan a sequence of interactions to achieve the goal, execute interactions one at a time verifying each step succeeded, handle dynamic page changes and loading states, implement rollback for failed sequences, and verify the end state matches the intended outcome", "option_d": "Take screenshots and use vision to understand pages", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "In a multi-agent system, what is the correct implementation for consensus building among agents with different opinions?", "option_a": "Always accept the majority opinion without discussion", "option_b": "Let the orchestrator override all agent opinions", "option_c": "Implement a structured consensus protocol: each agent presents its position with supporting evidence, agents identify points of agreement and disagreement, focused discussion on disagreements with evidence exchange, weighted voting considering agent expertise on the specific topic, clear documentation of the consensus rationale and any minority dissents", "option_d": "Randomly select one agent's opinion as the final answer", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that can detect and adapt to changes in the external environment, what is the correct monitoring approach?", "option_a": "Never check for environmental changes", "option_b": "Re-check the entire environment before every action", "option_c": "Implement selective monitoring: identify critical environmental variables for the current task, set up change detection on those variables (polling or event-driven), trigger plan reassessment when significant changes are detected, distinguish between changes that require adaptation vs those that are noise, and implement graceful strategy shifts without losing progress", "option_d": "Only check the environment at the start of each task", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct pattern for implementing an agent that can generate and execute test plans for software features?", "option_a": "Only run pre-written test scripts", "option_b": "Generate random test inputs without strategy", "option_c": "Analyze the feature specification to identify test scenarios (happy paths, edge cases, error conditions, integration points), generate test cases with expected outcomes, execute tests and compare actual vs expected results, report failures with diagnostic information, suggest additional tests based on code coverage analysis, and prioritize tests by risk", "option_d": "Only test the main happy path scenario", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
