    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that needs to explain its actions in natural language for transparency, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Return the raw LLM generation log", "option_b": "Only explain when asked, never proactively", "option_c": "Generate a single-sentence explanation for all actions", "option_d": "Maintain an explanation graph linking actions to goals: for each action, record why it was chosen (reasoning), what alternatives were considered, what evidence supported the decision, what the expected outcome was, and generate natural language explanations at appropriate detail levels for different audiences (end users vs developers vs auditors)", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation for an agent that handles progressive task refinement based on intermediate results?", "option_a": "Execute the initial plan without any refinement", "option_b": "Completely restart planning after each step", "option_c": "Only refine the plan once at the halfway point", "option_d": "After each significant intermediate result, evaluate whether the result changes the understanding of the overall task, identify new subtasks that emerged or existing ones that became unnecessary, adjust priorities and approach based on what was learned, maintain continuity with work already completed, and communicate plan changes to stakeholders", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "In an agent architecture, what is the correct approach for implementing a system that evaluates the cost-benefit of taking additional actions?\n\ncode:\nclass CostBenefitAgent:\n    def should_continue(self, current_state, potential_actions):\n        ???", "option_a": "Always continue until no more actions are possible", "option_b": "Stop after a fixed number of actions", "option_c": "Only consider monetary cost, not time or quality", "option_d": "Estimate the marginal benefit of each potential action (expected improvement in outcome quality), compare against the marginal cost (tokens, latency, money, risk of making things worse), implement diminishing returns detection, and stop when no available action has positive expected net value - satisficing when the current result is good enough", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing a multi-agent system for software development, what is the correct division of responsibilities?", "option_a": "One agent does everything from planning to deployment", "option_b": "Only split into frontend and backend agents", "option_c": "Create one agent per file in the repository", "option_d": "Implement specialized agents: architect (designs systems and interfaces), implementer (writes code following designs), reviewer (checks code quality and correctness), tester (generates and runs tests), deployer (manages deployment safely) - with clear handoff protocols, shared artifact store, and an orchestrator that manages the development lifecycle", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},

    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation for an agent that uses dynamic prompt construction based on the current execution context?", "option_a": "Use a fixed prompt template for all situations", "option_b": "Randomly select from a pool of prompt variants", "option_c": "Let the user write prompts manually each time", "option_d": "Assemble the prompt dynamically by selecting components based on context: include relevant tool descriptions (only currently applicable tools), inject recent memory entries related to the current task, add appropriate few-shot examples for the current action type, include relevant constraints and guardrails, and optimize for token efficiency by excluding irrelevant context", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that needs to handle conflicting instructions from different sources, what is the correct priority resolution?", "option_a": "Always follow the most recent instruction", "option_b": "Follow all instructions simultaneously", "option_c": "Ignore all conflicting instructions and ask the user", "option_d": "Implement a clear instruction hierarchy: system-level safety constraints (highest priority, cannot be overridden), application-level policies, user-level preferences, and current session instructions - with explicit conflict detection that logs the conflict, applies the highest-priority applicable rule, and optionally notifies about overridden instructions", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that can manage and track assumptions it's making during execution?", "option_a": "Never make assumptions; always ask for clarification", "option_b": "Make assumptions silently without tracking them", "option_c": "Only track assumptions when they turn out to be wrong", "option_d": "Explicitly tag each assumption made during reasoning (what was assumed, why it's reasonable, what would change if wrong), track assumptions in a structured store, validate assumptions when new information becomes available, trigger plan revision when assumptions are invalidated, and present key assumptions to users for verification at appropriate points", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "In an agent architecture, what is the correct pattern for implementing a backtracking mechanism when a chosen approach fails?", "option_a": "Always continue forward regardless of failures", "option_b": "Restart completely from the beginning", "option_c": "Only backtrack one step at a time", "option_d": "Maintain a decision tree with choice points, when a path fails identify the root decision that led to failure (not just the last step), restore state to that choice point, mark the failed path to avoid repetition, select an alternative approach informed by why the previous one failed, and carry forward any valid intermediate results from the abandoned path", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that needs to collaborate with human team members asynchronously, what is the correct communication pattern?", "option_a": "Block until humans respond to every message", "option_b": "Never wait for human input; always proceed independently", "option_c": "Only communicate at the beginning and end of tasks", "option_d": "Implement async collaboration: send updates at meaningful milestones (not every action), clearly mark items needing human input vs FYI updates, continue with other tasks while waiting for responses, handle delayed/partial responses gracefully, maintain a clear shared understanding of current state and next steps, and respect human communication preferences for timing and format", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation for an agent that can identify when it needs help from a more capable system or human?", "option_a": "Never ask for help; always try independently", "option_b": "Ask for help on every task regardless of difficulty", "option_c": "Only escalate when a hard error occurs", "option_d": "Implement self-awareness of capability boundaries: detect low confidence in reasoning, recognize task types outside training/experience, identify when repeated attempts aren't making progress, assess the risk of proceeding with uncertainty - and escalate with a clear description of what was attempted, what's known, what's uncertain, and what specific help is needed", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
