    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that can generate and maintain system architecture documentation?", "option_a": "Only document what the developer manually describes", "option_b": "Analyze the codebase structure (imports, dependencies, communication patterns, data flow), infrastructure configuration, and deployment topology to generate architecture documentation; keep it synchronized with code changes; identify undocumented components and integration points; generate both high-level overviews and detailed component descriptions", "option_c": "Generate documentation once and never update it", "option_d": "Only produce UML diagrams without text explanations", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "In a multi-agent system for automated customer support, what is the correct escalation pattern?", "option_a": "Never escalate; the first agent must handle everything", "option_b": "Escalate after every 3 messages regardless of resolution progress", "option_c": "Implement intelligent escalation: detect when the current agent's capabilities are insufficient (repeated misunderstandings, increasing user frustration, complex multi-system issues), select the appropriate specialist agent or human based on issue classification, transfer full context with a summary of what was tried, and ensure seamless conversation continuity", "option_d": "Always route directly to human agents", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation for an agent that manages its own prompt through meta-prompting?", "option_a": "Use a static prompt without any self-modification", "option_b": "Let the agent modify its own core safety instructions", "option_c": "Only adjust tone without changing capabilities", "option_d": "Allow the agent to propose modifications to its non-safety prompt components (examples, formatting instructions, tool usage guidance) based on performance feedback, validate proposed changes against a quality benchmark, implement A/B testing of prompt variants, maintain version history with rollback, and protect core behavioral constraints from modification", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that needs to reason about spatial relationships (e.g., for robotics or UI layout), what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Maintain an explicit spatial representation (coordinate system, bounding boxes, relative positions), use structured spatial reasoning operators (overlap detection, containment, adjacency), translate spatial queries into geometric computations, and combine spatial reasoning with LLM-based semantic understanding for tasks like 'place the button near the navigation menu'", "option_b": "Rely solely on the LLM's implicit spatial understanding", "option_c": "Only reason about 1D relationships (before/after)", "option_d": "Avoid all spatial reasoning tasks", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct pattern for implementing an agent that performs impact analysis before executing changes?", "option_a": "Execute changes without impact analysis for speed", "option_b": "Before executing any change, identify all potentially affected components (downstream dependencies, users, services), estimate the blast radius, classify potential impacts by severity, generate a risk assessment report, recommend mitigation strategies (gradual rollout, feature flags, monitoring), and require appropriate approval based on impact level", "option_c": "Only analyze impact after the change is deployed", "option_d": "Only consider direct dependencies without transitive effects", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "In an agent architecture, what is the correct approach for implementing context-dependent behavior switching?", "option_a": "Use the same behavior regardless of context", "option_b": "Maintain a library of behavior profiles (e.g., 'careful mode' for sensitive operations, 'creative mode' for brainstorming, 'fast mode' for simple queries), detect context signals that indicate which profile is appropriate, switch smoothly between profiles, allow user override of detected mode, and maintain consistency within a mode while being adaptive across modes", "option_c": "Create separate agent instances for each behavior mode", "option_d": "Let users manually specify the behavior mode for every interaction", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that handles complex multi-step data transformation pipelines, what is the correct architecture?", "option_a": "Transform all data in a single step", "option_b": "Hard-code all transformation logic without flexibility", "option_c": "Design transformations as composable steps: each step has clear input/output schemas, implement validation between steps, support branching and merging of data flows, allow the agent to dynamically compose transformation sequences based on the goal, checkpoint intermediate results for debugging, and provide rollback to any intermediate state", "option_d": "Only support predefined transformation templates", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that handles graceful shutdown and task handoff?", "option_a": "Terminate immediately when shutdown is requested", "option_b": "Ignore shutdown signals until all tasks complete (potentially forever)", "option_c": "Drop all pending tasks without notification", "option_d": "On shutdown signal: stop accepting new tasks, allow in-progress tasks a grace period to reach a safe checkpoint, persist the state of incomplete tasks with full context for handoff, notify dependent agents/users of pending handoff, and provide a structured handoff package that another agent instance can resume from", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "In a production agent system, what is the correct approach for implementing progressive confidence building?", "option_a": "Assume maximum confidence for all outputs from the start", "option_b": "Never increase confidence regardless of evidence", "option_c": "Start with low confidence on new task types, accumulate evidence through tool use and reasoning, track confidence calibration (how often high-confidence outputs are correct), increase confidence as evidence accumulates, decrease when contradictions appear, and communicate confidence level to users to set appropriate expectations for the output", "option_d": "Only use binary confident/not-confident classification", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation for an agent that can learn from and adapt to user interaction patterns over a session?", "option_a": "Treat each message independently without pattern learning", "option_b": "Observe user behavior patterns within the session (preferred response length, level of detail desired, common follow-up questions, formatting preferences), adapt responses to match observed preferences without being explicitly told, validate adaptations by monitoring user satisfaction signals, and reset learned patterns between unrelated sessions while preserving universal preferences", "option_c": "Ask the user to fill out a preferences form at session start", "option_d": "Apply the same style regardless of user signals", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing a multi-agent system for automated deployment, what safety guarantees must the architecture provide?", "option_a": "Deploy without any safety checks for speed", "option_b": "Only deploy during maintenance windows", "option_c": "Never automate deployments", "option_d": "Implement deployment guardrails: automated health checks before/after each stage, canary deployments with automatic rollback on metric degradation, blast radius limits (percentage of traffic exposed), multi-agent consensus for production changes (deploy agent proposes, verify agent validates, monitor agent confirms health), and complete audit trail", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that can handle ambiguity in tool selection?", "option_a": "Always ask the user which tool to use", "option_b": "When multiple tools could serve the current need: evaluate each candidate tool's suitability (past success rate in similar contexts, expected cost, expected quality), consider whether tools can be tried cheaply (read-only tools can be tried speculatively), implement a decision framework that selects optimally based on current context, and learn from outcomes to improve future selection", "option_c": "Use the first matching tool without evaluation", "option_d": "Randomly select from matching tools", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "In an agent architecture, what is the correct way to implement a knowledge distillation pipeline?", "option_a": "Use the same LLM for all tasks regardless of difficulty", "option_b": "Only use large models without distillation", "option_c": "Generate high-quality training examples using a large model (GPT-4), curate and validate the examples, fine-tune a smaller model on these examples for specific agent tasks, evaluate the smaller model against the large model on held-out scenarios, deploy the smaller model for production (faster/cheaper) with the large model as fallback for edge cases, and continuously add new examples", "option_d": "Replace the large model entirely without validation", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that helps users debug issues, what is the correct diagnostic reasoning pattern?", "option_a": "Ask users to try random solutions", "option_b": "Only suggest restarting the system", "option_c": "Always ask for all possible information before diagnosing", "option_d": "Use systematic diagnostic reasoning: gather initial symptoms, form differential diagnosis (multiple possible causes ranked by likelihood), ask targeted questions that maximally differentiate between candidates, narrow hypotheses with each piece of new evidence, suggest the most likely fix first with verification steps, and escalate if initial diagnoses are disproven", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct pattern for implementing an agent that manages its own tool ecosystem (adding, updating, deprecating tools)?", "option_a": "Fix the tool set permanently at deployment time", "option_b": "Add every tool suggested without evaluation", "option_c": "Let users manage all tools manually", "option_d": "Implement a tool lifecycle manager: evaluate new tools against integration criteria (safety, reliability, necessity), add tools through a staged process (sandbox testing -> limited deployment -> general availability), monitor tool usage and effectiveness, deprecate tools that are no longer useful or have better alternatives, and maintain backward compatibility during transitions", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that performs code review focusing on security vulnerabilities, what is the correct architecture?", "option_a": "Analyze code changes against known vulnerability patterns (injection, authentication bypass, data exposure, insecure defaults), understand the application context to assess real exploitability, check for missing security controls (input validation, output encoding, access checks), prioritize findings by severity and confidence, suggest specific fixes, and verify fixes don't introduce new issues", "option_b": "Only run static analysis tools without LLM understanding", "option_c": "Flag any use of user input as a potential vulnerability", "option_d": "Only review code that explicitly handles authentication", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that generates and validates database queries from user intent?", "option_a": "Generate queries without validation and execute directly", "option_b": "Only allow predefined query templates", "option_c": "Require users to write SQL directly", "option_d": "Parse user intent into a structured query plan, generate SQL using schema awareness and the intent, validate syntax with a parser, check semantic correctness (referenced tables/columns exist, types match), estimate query cost/performance, run in a sandboxed read-only environment first, present results with explanation of what the query does, and support iterative refinement", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "In a production multi-agent system, what is the correct approach for implementing agent performance benchmarking?", "option_a": "Define standardized benchmark suites covering each agent's domain: accuracy metrics (task success rate, output quality), efficiency metrics (tokens used, steps taken, latency), safety metrics (guardrail violations, harmful outputs), and reliability metrics (error rate, recovery time) - running benchmarks regularly, comparing across versions, and detecting degradation automatically", "option_b": "Only measure response time", "option_c": "Rely on user complaints to identify performance issues", "option_d": "Benchmark only at initial deployment", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that coordinates multiple data sources for decision-making, what is the correct information fusion approach?", "option_a": "Only use the first data source that returns results", "option_b": "Average values from all sources without considering reliability", "option_c": "Implement weighted information fusion: assign reliability scores to each source based on historical accuracy, detect conflicting information across sources, apply source-appropriate weighting (authoritative sources get higher weight), cross-validate critical facts across multiple sources, maintain provenance for all data points, and present the fused result with confidence indicators", "option_d": "Only use the most expensive data source", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation for an agent system that supports plugin-based extensibility?", "option_a": "Allow arbitrary code execution from plugins", "option_b": "Implement a plugin SDK with sandboxed execution: plugins declare capabilities via a manifest, the agent loads plugins that match current task needs, plugins execute in isolation with limited resource access, communication happens through defined interfaces, plugins are versioned and can be hot-swapped, and malicious plugin behavior is detected and blocked", "option_c": "Hard-code all functionality without extensibility", "option_d": "Only allow plugins written by the same team", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},

    # Additional mixed questions to reach exact count (questions 801-900)
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that needs to generate migration plans for legacy systems, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Migrate everything simultaneously in a big-bang approach", "option_b": "Only migrate the newest components", "option_c": "Analyze the legacy system's components, dependencies, and data flows; identify migration candidates ordered by risk and value; generate incremental migration plans that maintain system functionality at each step; create validation checkpoints; plan rollback strategies for each migration phase; and estimate effort and risk per component", "option_d": "Let the agent decide which systems to keep and which to discard", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct pattern for implementing an agent that manages configuration across multiple environments?", "option_a": "Use the same configuration for all environments", "option_b": "Manually manage each environment independently", "option_c": "Let the agent modify production config without approval", "option_d": "Implement environment-aware configuration management: maintain base configs with environment-specific overrides, validate configs against schemas before applying, detect drift between environments, suggest harmonization where appropriate, require approval workflows for production changes, and maintain full config change history with diff capabilities", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing a system that uses OpenAI for intelligent retry strategy selection, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Use the same retry strategy for all errors", "option_b": "Never retry any failed request", "option_c": "Classify the error type and select an appropriate retry strategy: transient errors (network timeout) get immediate retry with exponential backoff; rate limits respect the Retry-After header; validation errors get prompt modification and retry; model errors get model fallback; and unknown errors get logged for investigation without retry", "option_d": "Retry all errors exactly 3 times with 1-second intervals", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that summarizes and prioritizes information from multiple tool outputs?", "option_a": "Present all tool outputs raw without processing", "option_b": "Only show the first tool's output", "option_c": "Randomly select which outputs to present", "option_d": "Score each tool output by relevance to the current query, identify key information across all outputs, detect and resolve contradictions between sources, synthesize a coherent summary highlighting the most important findings, maintain source attribution, and present information in order of relevance with drill-down capability", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an OpenAI-powered system for automated test failure analysis, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Only report that tests failed without analysis", "option_b": "Analyze the test failure output (error messages, stack traces, diff from expected), correlate with recent code changes (git blame), identify the likely root cause, classify as regression vs flaky vs environment issue, suggest a fix or identify the responsible code change, and batch related failures into a single issue", "option_c": "Ask developers to analyze all failures manually", "option_d": "Re-run failed tests without analysis", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation for an agent that handles task dependencies in a complex workflow?", "option_a": "Execute all tasks in parallel ignoring dependencies", "option_b": "Execute all tasks strictly sequentially even independent ones", "option_c": "Build a dependency DAG from task relationships, identify critical path for timeline estimation, execute independent tasks in parallel, wait for dependencies before starting dependent tasks, handle dependency failures gracefully (retry, skip with fallback, abort downstream), and dynamically adjust execution order as tasks complete or fail", "option_d": "Let users manually specify execution order", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing a system that uses OpenAI for intelligent auto-completion in a domain-specific IDE, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Use generic code completion without domain context", "option_b": "Only suggest from previously typed code", "option_c": "Provide domain-specific context (project patterns, custom libraries, coding standards, recent changes) along with the current cursor position and surrounding code; generate completions that match project style; rank by relevance and correctness; support multi-line completions for common patterns; and learn from accepted/rejected suggestions", "option_d": "Only suggest single tokens at a time", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that can detect and respond to emotional cues in user messages?", "option_a": "Ignore emotional content and only address factual queries", "option_b": "Always respond with excessive empathy regardless of context", "option_c": "Assume all users are frustrated and apologize preemptively", "option_d": "Detect emotional signals (frustration, confusion, urgency, satisfaction) from language patterns and context, adapt response tone and approach accordingly (more patient when confused, more direct when urgent), acknowledge emotions when appropriate without being patronizing, adjust information density and pacing, and escalate to humans when strong negative emotions are detected", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing a system that uses OpenAI for automated infrastructure documentation, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Document infrastructure manually without LLM assistance", "option_b": "Only generate documentation from terraform/IaC files", "option_c": "Parse infrastructure-as-code files, cloud provider configurations, and monitoring setups; generate human-readable documentation of the architecture; include diagrams (as mermaid/plantuml code), runbooks for common operations, dependency maps, cost breakdowns, and security considerations; keep docs synchronized with actual infrastructure changes via CI/CD hooks", "option_d": "Generate a single paragraph describing the entire infrastructure", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct pattern for implementing an agent that validates its own outputs before presenting them?", "option_a": "Present all outputs without validation", "option_b": "Only validate format, not content", "option_c": "Always require human validation of every output", "option_d": "Implement a multi-layer self-validation pipeline: check format compliance (schema, length, structure), verify factual claims against available sources, test logical consistency (no contradictions within the output), validate against task requirements (all asked questions answered, constraints satisfied), and gate output delivery on validation passing with fallback strategies for failures", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing a system that uses OpenAI for personalizing documentation for different user segments, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Write one version of documentation for all users", "option_b": "Identify user segments (beginner/intermediate/expert, role-specific), maintain base documentation with marked extensibility points, generate segment-appropriate versions (more examples for beginners, API details for developers, business context for managers), validate each version for accuracy, and track which version produces better user outcomes per segment", "option_c": "Let users choose their documentation version manually", "option_d": "Only generate documentation for expert users", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation for an agent system that supports hot-swapping of underlying models without downtime?", "option_a": "Restart the entire system for model changes", "option_b": "Implement model abstraction with runtime switching: maintain a model registry with health checks, support gradual traffic migration between models, normalize different model outputs to a common format, implement automatic quality monitoring during transitions, support instant rollback if quality degrades, and maintain session continuity during model switches", "option_c": "Never change models once deployed", "option_d": "Force all users to reconnect when models change", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that generates and maintains API integration tests, what is the correct lifecycle approach?", "option_a": "Generate tests once and never update them", "option_b": "Only test happy paths without error scenarios", "option_c": "Let the agent manually run tests each time", "option_d": "Generate tests covering happy paths, error cases, edge cases, and contract validation; integrate tests into CI/CD pipeline; detect when API changes invalidate tests (schema changes, new endpoints); automatically regenerate affected tests; maintain test data fixtures; track test flakiness; and report coverage gaps relative to the API surface", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that performs root cause analysis of production incidents?", "option_a": "Collect data from multiple sources (logs, metrics, traces, recent deployments, configuration changes), correlate events by timeline, identify anomalies that preceded the incident, trace causation chains from symptom to root cause, generate hypotheses ranked by evidence strength, suggest immediate mitigations and long-term fixes, and produce a structured incident report", "option_b": "Only look at the most recent error log", "option_c": "Blame the last deployment without investigation", "option_d": "Wait for the incident to resolve itself", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "In a multi-agent system, what is the correct implementation for preventing information leakage between agent contexts?", "option_a": "Share all information freely between all agents", "option_b": "Implement strict context isolation: each agent only receives information it needs for its specific task (need-to-know basis), sanitize data crossing agent boundaries, implement information classification levels, audit cross-agent data transfers, prevent sensitive information from one user's session leaking into another's through shared agent state, and implement memory wiping between unrelated sessions", "option_c": "Let agents decide what to share", "option_d": "Block all inter-agent communication", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing a system that uses OpenAI for intelligent API gateway routing, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Analyze incoming request content and metadata to determine optimal routing: classify request intent, estimate required processing time, route to appropriate backend service based on content analysis, implement intelligent load balancing that considers both server capacity and request complexity, detect misrouted requests through response analysis, and adapt routing rules based on observed patterns", "option_b": "Route all requests to the same backend", "option_c": "Route based solely on URL path matching", "option_d": "Randomly distribute requests for load balancing", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct pattern for implementing an agent that handles concurrent access to shared external resources?", "option_a": "Ignore concurrency and hope for the best", "option_b": "Serialize all access to external resources", "option_c": "Implement distributed locking for exclusive resources, optimistic concurrency control for shared resources, conflict detection and resolution strategies, retry with backoff on conflicts, resource pooling for frequently accessed resources, and monitoring for deadlocks with automatic resolution", "option_d": "Create dedicated resource instances for each agent", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing a system that uses OpenAI for dynamic report generation, what ensures output quality?", "option_a": "Generate reports without structure or templates", "option_b": "Only use static report templates", "option_c": "Generate the same report format regardless of data", "option_d": "Define report schemas with required sections and data elements, generate content that maps data to narrative explanations, validate all numbers and calculations, ensure visualizations match described data, implement human-in-the-loop review for high-stakes reports, support iterative refinement based on reviewer feedback, and maintain report versioning", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that generates and maintains runbooks for operational procedures?", "option_a": "Write all runbooks manually without agent assistance", "option_b": "Generate runbooks once and never update them", "option_c": "Analyze operational patterns (common incidents, resolution steps, system dependencies), generate step-by-step runbooks with decision trees for different scenarios, validate steps against actual system state, include automated health check commands, maintain versioned runbooks that update as systems change, and test runbooks against simulated scenarios periodically", "option_d": "Only document procedures after they're followed successfully 10 times", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an OpenAI-powered system for dynamic content tagging and categorization, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Analyze content semantics to assign tags from a managed taxonomy, support hierarchical categorization, detect new categories that emerge from content (suggest taxonomy updates), handle multi-label classification with confidence scores, ensure consistency across similar content, and implement feedback loops that improve classification accuracy from corrections", "option_b": "Only use keyword-based tagging without semantic understanding", "option_c": "Let users manually tag all content", "option_d": "Assign random tags from the taxonomy", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},

    # Final batch of questions (questions 901-1000) - carefully balanced
    {"question_text": "When implementing an agent that autonomously manages cloud infrastructure, what safety constraints are essential?", "option_a": "Allow unrestricted infrastructure changes for full autonomy", "option_b": "Only allow viewing infrastructure without any changes", "option_c": "Require manual approval for every single change", "option_d": "Implement guardrails: define allowed actions per environment (read-only in prod by default), enforce change budgets (max instances, cost limits), require escalating approvals based on blast radius, implement dry-run before actual execution, maintain automatic rollback triggers based on health metrics, and never allow security group/IAM changes without multi-factor approval", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for implementing an agent that optimizes its own token usage over time?", "option_a": "Always use maximum tokens for thoroughness", "option_b": "Track token usage patterns per task type, identify opportunities for compression (shorter prompts that achieve same quality, more efficient tool descriptions, better context selection), implement A/B testing of optimized vs original prompts, maintain quality metrics to ensure optimization doesn't degrade output, and progressively apply successful optimizations", "option_c": "Use minimum tokens for everything to save cost", "option_d": "Ignore token usage entirely", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing a system that uses OpenAI for intelligent alert correlation, what is the correct approach?", "option_a": "Treat each alert independently without correlation", "option_b": "Group alerts by exact error message match only", "option_c": "Analyze alert content, timing, and affected components to identify related alerts (same root cause), cluster correlated alerts into incidents, identify the probable root cause using temporal and causal analysis, generate incident summaries with timeline, and reduce alert noise by 80%+ through intelligent suppression of redundant notifications", "option_d": "Suppress all alerts during high-volume periods", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct implementation for an agent that generates and maintains a decision log?", "option_a": "Never document decisions", "option_b": "Only log decisions when asked by users", "option_c": "Log every micro-decision the agent makes", "option_d": "Record significant decisions with full context: what was decided, what alternatives were considered and why they were rejected, what information the decision was based on, what assumptions were made, what the expected outcome was, and what trigger conditions would warrant revisiting the decision - making the log searchable and linkable for accountability", "correct_answer": "D", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "agent_architecture"},
    {"question_text": "When implementing an OpenAI-powered system for extracting key metrics from financial documents, what safety measures are required?", "option_a": "Trust all extracted numbers without verification", "option_b": "Implement multi-pass extraction: first pass extracts candidate values, second pass validates against internal consistency (totals match line items, percentages sum correctly), cross-reference with other document sections, flag uncertain extractions with confidence scores, require human verification for material financial figures, and maintain complete audit trail of extraction logic", "option_c": "Only extract numbers that appear in tables", "option_d": "Round all numbers to avoid precision issues", "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
    {"question_text": "What is the correct approach for an agent that needs to generate commit messages from code diffs?", "option_a": "Analyze the code diff to understand the semantic change (what was modified, why it was likely done based on code context), generate a commit message following conventional commit format, include scope/type classification, summarize the user-facing impact, and reference related issues if detectable from branch names or code comments", "option_b": "Copy the diff as the commit message", "option_c": "Generate a random generic commit message", "option_d": "Only include file names that changed", "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "llm_apis"},
